Kani `verify-rust-std` harness `core::ptr::verify::check_align_offset_u32`,
a CBMC v6 goto-binary. It performs a whole-array value load (`[u8; N] = *ptr`)
which reaches ESBMC as an array-typed dereference target. (The `_u8` width of
this harness happens to avoid the array-typed target and so does not exercise
the fix; `_u32` does.)

Before construct_array_ref (see src/pointer-analysis/dereference.cpp) this
aborted with "Can't construct rvalue reference to array type during
dereference". It now reaches VERIFICATION FAILED, matching CBMC 6.10.0 on the
same binary (the failing property is a Kani reachability_check coverage marker,
not a real assertion violation).

The array-rvalue shape is produced only by Kani's Rust->goto compiler; neither
C/C++ nor goto-cc persists it, so this is validated against the committed Kani
binary rather than a regenerable C source.
